<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-577-870  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 577 870.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Transactions on Robotics and Automation  June 1989 v5 n3p294(9).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Dynamics computation of closed-link robot mechanisms withnonredundant and redundant actuators. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Nakamura, Yoshihiko; Ghodoussi, Modjtaba.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A general and systematic computational model is developed of theinverse dynamics of closed-link mechanisms used in robotic arms.andO;Such mechanisms are useful in direct-drive robots, as the devicesallow driving motors to be located closer to the robot's base andare particulary suited for implementing parallel actuated robotarm wrists and fingers that possess multiple degrees of freedom ofmovement.andP;  The computationally efficient and comparatively simplescheme was developed through the use of d'Alembert's principle andwithout the need for computing the Lagrange multipliers.andP;  Detailsof the development of the model and use in a nonredundant actuatorsystem (the UCSB HAND of the Center for Robotic Systems inMicroelectronics at the Univ of California at Santa Barbara) aredescribed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Research and DevelopmentModelingDynamicsRobot ArmsSystem DesignSystems AnalysisServomechanismsCalifornia, University of (Santa Barbara).andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Equivalent transformation of closed-link mechanisms to open-linkmechanism. (chart)Finger structure of UCSB HAND. (chart)Gear reduction and transmission of UCSB HAND. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>